'''Mito Shrine''' (みとじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|qid=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} in Terada Mitosaka, {{ill|lt=Joyo|Q817276|qid=Q817276|1=Jōyō, Kyoto}}, {{ill|lt=Kyoto Prefecture|Q120730|qid=Q120730|1=Kyoto Prefecture}}. It is a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|qid=Q134917286}}, and its former rank was {{ill|Fu-sha|qid=Q134917326|1=Fu-sha}}.

Located at the foot of Kōnos巣-yama, it was the {{ill|lt=ubusunagami|Q1392097|qid=Q1392097|1=Ubusunagami}} of old {{ill|lt=Terada Village (Kyoto Prefecture)|Q30937244|qid=Q30937244|lt=Terada Village|1=Terada}}.

=== Enshrined deities ===
* {{ill|lt=Amaterasu|Q455602|qid=Q455602|lt=Amaterasu Sumemioya Ōkami|1=Amaterasu}} (あまてらすすめおおみかみ)
* {{ill|qid=Q125400|lt=Takamimusubi|UNKNOWN|qid=Q125400|lt=Takamimusubi-no-kami|1=Takamimusubi}} (たかみむすびのかみ)
* {{ill|qid=Q2329261|lt=Toyotama-hime no Mikoto|UNKNOWN|lt=Wadatsumi Toyotama-hime no Mikoto|1=Toyotama-hime}} (わだつみとよたまひめのみこと)

=== History ===
=== Overview ===
According to shrine tradition, the shrine was founded in the early {{ill|lt=Heian period|Q193292|qid=Q193292|1=Heian period}}, but because a fragment of ''Yamashiro no Kuni Fudoki'' records "Mito no yashiro in Mizuwatari, Kuse District," it is thought to have already existed in the {{ill|lt=Nara period|Q189178|qid=Q189178|1=Nara period}}, when the {{ill|lt=Fudoki|Q1194534|qid=Q1194534|1=Fudoki}} were compiled. In the {{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|qid=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}} compiled in the early Heian period, it appears as "Mito Shrine, three seats." It was ranked {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|qid=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}} in {{ill|lt=1873|Q7757|qid=Q7757|1=1873}} (Meiji 6), promoted to {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|qid=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in {{ill|lt=1882|Q7812|qid=Q7812|1=1882}} (Meiji 15), and promoted to {{ill|Fu-sha|qid=Q134917326|1=Fu-sha}} in {{ill|lt=1907|Q2048|qid=Q2048|1=1907}} (Meiji 40). The rank system was later abolished; it now belongs to {{ill|lt=Jinja Honcho|Q908077|qid=Q908077|1=Association of Shinto Shrines}} and is registered as "Religious Corporation Mito Shrine."

=== Divine rank ===
* {{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|qid=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} 3 ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|qid=Q23897|1=859}}), {{ill|lt=January 27|Q2284|qid=Q2284|1=January 27}}: promoted from Senior Sixth Rank Upper to Junior Fifth Rank Lower (''{{ill|lt=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|qid=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'') - recorded as "Mito no Kami."

=== Precinct ===
The honden is one-bay {{ill|lt=nagare-zukuri|Q210684|qid=Q210684|1=Nagare-zukuri}}, one bay front and two bays side. The roof is {{ill|lt=hinoki bark roofing|Q90373477|qid=Q90373477|1=cypress bark roof}} with a large {{ill|lt=chidori hafu|Q4881511|qid=Q4881511|1=Bargeboard}} gable on the front. At the center of the front porch are openwork {{ill|lt=karakusa pattern|Q732328|qid=Q732328|lt=arabesque|1=Scroll (art)}} carvings and {{ill|lt=kaerumata|Q123117911|qid=Q123117911|1=kaerumata}} braces, making a simple yet elegant structure. A {{ill|lt=munafuda|Q8008834|qid=Q8008834|1=Munafuda}} indicates construction in {{ill|lt=1448|Q6439|qid=Q6439|1=1448}} ({{ill|lt=Bun'an|Q1193586|qid=Q1193586|1=Bun'an}} 5) in the {{ill|lt=Muromachi period|Q334845|qid=Q334845|1=Muromachi period}}. It is the oldest surviving building in Joyo City and is designated a national {{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|qid=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}}.
